      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"total_weeks\":16,\"goal_description\":\"Return From Injury — Plantar Fasciitis Recovery & Base Rebuild\",\"phases\":[{\"phase_type\":\"Base\",\"weeks\":4,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":10,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":14,\"intensity_distribution\":\"100% easy (walk/run as needed)\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"Recovery\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":358,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":358,\"notes\":\"This phase is entirely about rebuilding tissue tolerance and movement confidence, not fitness. Every run stays at the easy end of your pace range (5:58/km or slower if your foot asks for it). Sessions are capped at 20 minutes, 3 days per week, with at least one full rest day between each run. If you feel any foot pain during a run, shift to a walk immediately — walking breaks are not a setback, they are the plan working. A deload week occurs in week 4, dropping back to roughly week 1 volume. The goal by the end of this phase is 3 consecutive weeks of pain-free running at 20 minutes per session.\",\"includes_deload\":true},{\"phase_type\":\"Base\",\"weeks\":4,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":14,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":20,\"intensity_distribution\":\"95% easy / 5% moderate\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"Recovery\",\"CrossTrain\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":351,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":344,\"notes\":\"Assuming your physiotherapist clears you to extend session duration beyond 20 minutes, this phase gently introduces longer easy efforts. Session length can grow from 20 to 30 minutes across the phase, but only if the previous week was fully pain-free. Cross-training (pool running, cycling, elliptical) is encouraged on non-running days to build aerobic capacity without additional foot loading. Pace stays firmly in the easy zone (5:24–5:58/km). A deload week in week 8 brings volume back down before the next build. No speed work of any kind — your foot needs consistent, low-stress loading before it can handle intensity.\",\"includes_deload\":true},{\"phase_type\":\"Build\",\"weeks\":4,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":20,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":28,\"intensity_distribution\":\"85% easy / 15% moderate\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"LongRun\",\"CrossTrain\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":344,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":324,\"notes\":\"This phase introduces a proper long run on Saturdays — starting at 35 minutes and building toward 50 minutes by the end of the phase. The other two weekly runs remain easy and shorter (25–30 minutes). Pace can shift toward the faster end of your easy range (5:24/km) on days when your foot feels strong, but there is no obligation to push. The 10% weekly volume cap is strictly observed. A deload in week 12 consolidates the gains before the final phase. Speed work remains off the table until you have explicit physiotherapist clearance — this is not a limitation, it is what protects the fitness you are rebuilding.\",\"includes_deload\":true},{\"phase_type\":\"Peak\",\"weeks\":4,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":28,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":35,\"intensity_distribution\":\"80% easy / 20% moderate (tempo only if cleared)\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"LongRun\",\"Tempo\",\"CrossTrain\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":338,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":269,\"notes\":\"By this phase you will have 12 weeks of consistent, pain-free running behind you — a genuinely strong foundation. If your physiotherapist has cleared you for moderate intensity work, one weekly run can include a short tempo segment (threshold pace 4:29/km) of no more than 10 minutes embedded in an easy run. If you are not yet cleared, this phase simply continues the Build pattern with longer easy runs. The long run reaches 55–60 minutes. The focus is arriving at the end of this plan feeling strong, healthy, and ready to set a new goal — whether that is a return to racing or simply enjoying running again. A deload in week 16 closes the plan with a recovery week that celebrates how far you have come.\",\"includes_deload\":true}],\"rationale\":\"James, your recent training history tells a genuinely encouraging story — you have been consistent, you have been patient, and your foot has been responding well. That 5-minute stiffness that resolved on its own on March 10th, and the clean run on March 17th, are exactly the signals we want to see. This plan is built on that momentum. The structure follows a conservative return-to-running model grounded in tissue remodeling physiology: plantar fascia responds to load, but it needs progressive, predictable load — not sudden spikes. Your VDOT of 46.5 from your pre-injury 10K tells us your aerobic engine is capable, but your foot's connective tissue is the limiting factor right now, not your fitness. That is why the early phases look almost too easy from a cardiovascular standpoint — they are deliberately designed that way. The 10% weekly volume rule is non-negotiable here, and deload weeks every 3–4 weeks give the fascia time to consolidate adaptation before the next build. Speed work is excluded until physiotherapist clearance because high-intensity running dramatically increases forefoot loading forces — exactly the tissue we are protecting. Cross-training is included as a genuine fitness tool, not a consolation prize: pool running and cycling can maintain a significant portion of your aerobic base while keeping foot stress low. The long run on Saturdays honors your stated preference and gives the week a clear anchor. By week 16, the goal is not just a healed foot — it is a James who is running 3 days a week, building toward his next race, with a body he can trust again.\",\"warnings\":\"This plan is built around your current physiotherapist clearance for 20 minutes of easy running only, with no speed work. Two things must happen before progressing between phases: (1) the previous phase must have been completed without recurring foot pain, and (2) any extension of session duration or introduction of intensity requires explicit physiotherapist sign-off — not just the absence of pain. If foot pain returns at any point, stop the session, revert to walk/run, and consult your physiotherapist before your next run. Do not redistribute missed mileage to other days. Missing a run is not a problem to fix — it is information to work with. This plan does not include a race target because your current priority is tissue health, not performance. Once you have completed this plan pain-free, you will be in an excellent position to set a new race goal and build toward it properly.\"}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
